In <4egolj$huj@news-e1a.megaweb.com>, JayWeber@gnn.com (Jim Bortmas) writes:
>Can anyone rank REXX functions, utilities and keyword commands
>by execution times. To improve my programming skills it would
>help to know what commands to avoid when alternative methods
>can be used. I don't expect a complete list so any guidance is
>appreciated.

The best answer, IMHO, is to write the application in a straight-forward and
readable manner, use the functions and statements which will allow you to
do that, and avoid the tricks and "neat hacks" to get around the "hog-ish"
command or function. In the long run, you'll be better off, and so will the
programmer that follows you.

If you go off on a witch hunt to avoid using SUBSTR or some other function,
chances are very good that in some future release of the REXX or operating
system you are using, the SUBSTR performance will be improved, and your
code will look silly to the next person that comes along after that.

Learn the language. Computers are (generally) fast enough now that individual
command or function performance within a language isn't supposed to be an
issue. (Before everyone flames, I know that's not always true; But it is supposed
to be the goal.) Use the language, and look at the overall performanace
afterward. Then, look at your methods first. You'll gain more performance by
improving your logic than you'll ever get by avoiding "hog-ish" functions, and
the application will perform better longer, and be more maintainable.

My two cents...

   Bob Nix

