In <4egolj$huj@news-e1a.megaweb.com>, JayWeber@gnn.com (Jim Bortmas) writes:
>Can anyone rank REXX functions, utilities and keyword commands
>by execution times. To improve my programming skills it would
>help to know what commands to avoid when alternative methods
>can be used. I don't expect a complete list so any guidance is
>appreciated.

This isn't intended to be a facile or rude response, but wouldn't finding
this for yourself out be an excellent way of working on your programming
skills?

You might want to bear in mind that REXX isn't intended to be a super-fast
or super-efficient language for running programs, but is rather intended
to be a language for easy writing of programs.

You will probably find that 99 times out of 100 using a REXX function or
command is the most efficient way to do something because while in the
function the code is running native machine code rather than interpreting
text. One good rule of thumb is to do things the easiest way possible. For
example, INTERPRET is difficult to use because it adds an extra layer
of interpretation which can be confusing to interpret (pun intended): it
is also slow because of the double interpretation, but it is sometimes
the only way to get something done.

